# Normalize line endings so the repo has one canonical representation (LF)
# regardless of whether a file was last edited on the Linux server or in
# RStudio/VS Code on Windows (via the X:\ SSHFS mount or the PC D clone).
#
# `text=auto` lets git auto-detect text vs binary; `eol=lf` forces LF both in
# the stored blob and on checkout, on every platform, overriding whatever
# core.autocrlf a given client (Windows Git/GitHub Desktop included) has set.
# This means: even if an editor writes CRLF back to disk, git normalizes it
# away on add/commit/diff/status, so line-ending-only "changes" never show up
# and files always check out as LF everywhere.
* text=auto eol=lf

*.R    text eol=lf
*.r    text eol=lf
*.qmd  text eol=lf
*.md   text eol=lf
*.sh   text eol=lf
*.csv  text eol=lf

# Explicit binary overrides (belt-and-suspenders on top of the text=auto
# heuristic) -- never line-ending-normalize these, and future-proofed for
# types not currently tracked but likely to be added (models, figures).
*.png    binary
*.xlsx   binary
*.pdf    binary
*.rds    binary
*.RData  binary
*.zip    binary
